tive and interfering influence of the government in education. I don't know of a single person who thinks that Ed Balls is anything other than loathsome creep, yet he somehow has the power to decide how most people's children are educated. In the past two years, in particular, the government has taken more and more powers to force even independent schools to comply with its requirements. For example, are you familiar with EYFS? It's a load of prescriptive nonsense and allows school staff and parents little scope for flexibility or to make their own decisions on how best to teach children. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="895" language="en" documentId="875" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="HJHJ" date="06 November 2009 2:43pm" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://discussion.theguardian.com/comment-permalink/6743502" topic="homeschooling" thumbsUp="19" thumbsDown="0" origId="875" notes="" title="Ridiculous rules for home schools"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="8"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="9" end="199"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="200" end="895"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43 47"/></xmi:XMI>